Gets this one to shape back in from outside off, Taylor looks to defend but once again there is extra bounce, it hits the splice and rolls towards point.
Good running! Shorter and on off, Williamson stands tall and drops it towards cover and takes one.
Drags his length back this time and it is outside off, Williamson does not fiddle with it.
Crisp drive but for no runs! Fuller and on off, Williamson strokes it right off the middle but towards short cover.
Another length delivery around off, Taylor guides it towards point, he wanted a run but is sent back. A dot means it is a wicket maiden from JH. Australia bowlers could have not started any better.
Good delivery first up to Taylor. Made him play. On a length and around off, it is kept out.
Ross Taylor is the next batsman in. The two New Zealand have out there, hold the key. Both scored tons against England in the last Test and they need a similar effort here.

OUT! KABOOM! Number two is down in the second over itself! So Raval does go early and has been knocked over. Hazlewood too has a wicket to his name. Gets the line right, gets the length right and that is the end of Raval. It is fuller and around middle and off. It tails back in late. Raval fails to adjust to the movement. He tries to flick it in the end but misses. It hits the pads and then the stumps. Another low score for Raval and New Zealand are in big trouble here.
Closer to the off pole than the last ball, not close enough to make the batter play though.
This one is outside off again but it does not come back in. Easy leave.

OHHH! That is pretty close. This starts outside off and it comes back in late. Raval lets it be and it goes just over the off pole. He may have not expected it to come back so much but in the end it turned out to be a good leave.
Josh Hazlewood to bowl from the other end.

A huge shout by Paine but not given! Down the leg side, Williamson looks to flick but misses. There is a sound as the ball passes the batter. Paine takes it and appeals but Starc is not interested. Replay shows it is off the thigh pad. End of a successful first for Starc.
Kane Williamson is the new man in. The skipper needs to play a solid knock here.

OUT! In the air... taken! Latham is out of here for a duck! Now, now, now, who expected that? Everyone would have put his money on Jeet Raval to go early. Mitchell Starc draws first blood. The extra bounce does Latham in. It is shorter and on the body, Latham looks to work it on the leg side but there is extra bounce. He does try to take his hand off the handle but too late. It hits the higher part and lobs back towards the bowler. He takes a dolly moving to his right. An early breakthrough, just the start Australia wanted. Also, a good wicket as Latham is known to play long innings.
Good delivery and well played in the end! Shorter and on off, it keeps rising after bouncing. Latham does well to pull his bat out of the way right at the end.
Raval is underway! A little too straight again, Raval looks to flick but gets an inside edge onto the pads. It rolls on the leg side and a single is taken.
A little too straight and the length is also shorter. Raval looks to leave it but is hit on the thigh pad.
Starts off with a very full delivery on middle, no swing on offer for Starc. Raval is solid in defense as he shows the full face of the bat.

The Aussies are already out in the middle. Pat Cummins is warming up, bowling through his run up. Jeet Raval and Tom Latham punch their gloves outside the boundary. Got a massive job ahead. Wait a minute. The Aussies are back in. Tim Paine gathers his troops and gives them some last-minute instructions. Now, both sets of players head out to the middle, following the umpires. Mitchell Starc to start off proceedings. Jeet Raval to face. Tom Latham being his partner. Here we go...

Australia would be happy with their second dig. Got Joe Burns back into form who played really well on a testing track. Around an hour left for Lunch. How many wickets will fall in this passage? Can the Kiwis have their openers intact into the break?

A 5-fer for Southee, on a wicket which has now started to do plenty of things. Yes, Australia are one bowler short, but this track is becoming deadly difficult to bat on. Expect the Aussies to return the short stuff favour to the Kiwis and someone needs to stand up. Technically, chasing down 468 in a scheduled allotted 165 overs is possible. But practically, on this track, batting for two whole days, to, forget a win, forge a draw either, is going to be challenging.

73 legal balls is all that New Zealand had to field today. This was coming, given that Australia had only one proper batsman in the middle in Matthew Wade. Yes, Pat Cummins can hang around but the short stuff from Wagner hurt the Aussies in their minds. They were caught in no man's land, unable to score and unable to defend and eventually lost their wickets.

Looks like Tim Paine is calling his men back. Because Nathan Lyon is rushing off the field, along with Mitchell Starc. Yup. Confirmed. Josh Hazlewood is not going to have to face the short-ball music as AUSTRALIA HAVE DECLARED, SETTING A TARGET OF 468.

OUT! Caught at fly slip! Brilliant captaincy from Williamson to keep a fielder in that position. With Starc going after the balls so hard, edges flying through the slips are always on the cards. Exactly what happened. Fullish length ball outside off, Starc looks to power it over long off but gets a thick outside edge which goes straight to Taylor at fly slip who makes no mistake. Fifer for Southee. It's been a hard toil for the pacers and the Kiwi bowler kept coming hard and has got a fifer to his name.
In the channel outside off, Lyon pokes but gets beaten.
Another bumper on middle, Starc pulls but has his eyes off the ball. Somehow manages to pull it towards square leg for a single.
WIDE! Another bumper but line is wrong. Starc ducks under it. Watling collects it on the bounce. Called wide as it is way down the leg side.
Slower yorker this time. Starc keeps it out nicely.
FOUR! Top edge but Starc won't care. Another bouncer on middle, Starc looks to pull it away but gets a top edge which flies over the keeper and to the fence.
Another short ball down the leg side. Starc ducks under it.
Back of a length ball down the leg side. Starc lets it be.
Defended off the back foot by the batsman.
A bouncer down the leg side, ducked under.
A down the leg side short leg side, tucked towards short leg.
Outside off, Mitchell punches it towards cover where the fielder misfields due to extra bounce. A single taken off the deflection.
Outside off, a slash and a miss.
A short ball, outside off, pulled straight to short mid-wicket.

FOUR LEG BYES! Bizarre decision from umpire Nigel Llong. A few overs ago, he signalled a dead ball when Wade did not offer a shot. A similar case for Nathan Lyon, but this time, he has awarded runs to Australia. A short ball, down the leg side, Lyon looks to tuck but then shoulders arms. The ball hits his pads and trickles to the fine leg fence. The lead is now 460.
A short ball now, around leg, Nathan fens it down in front of short leg.
A length ball, around middle, defended towards silly point.
Around middle and leg, tucked wide of short leg, towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
A man goes out to deep mid-wicket.
FOUR! ADMONISHED! A short ball, around middle, Starc pulls it through mid-wicket. Consecutive boundaries. The tail-enders would be looking to have some fun.
FOUR! Heaved away! A length ball, around middle, Starc heaves it wide of short mid-wicket. There is no one down the ground. A boundary. 200 UP FOR AUSTRALIA, LEAD CROSSES 450.
Full and around off, well blocked out.
Around off, pushed towards cover.
Down the leg side, Lyon misses his tuck and is hit on the box. Ouch.
Full and outside off, flayed through the covers for a single.
FOUR! A length ball outside off, Starc just heaves it over mid off and clears the man. A bounce and into the fence.
Outside off, left alone.
A short ball outside off, pulled wide of mid on for three runs. The lead is now 442.

Interesting. Josh Hazlewood is padded up. Is he REALLY needed today? Okay... the lead is just 442. And if New Zealand bat for two whole days on a track which is ready to explode, yeah makes sense to ensure that you bat for two sessions at least today, with tail-enders in the middle. Bizarre from Australia. Also, JOSH HAZLEWOOD HAS BEEN RULED OUT OF THE BOXING DAY TEST. Here comes Tim Southee. 19-6-63-4 so far.
Comes over the wickets, bowls it short, Mitchell looks to tuck it away and almost hits it into the hands of short leg. Just short and wide.
Another one down the leg side, shorter as well, left alone.
Around off, defended solidly.
Down the leg side, left alone.
Full ball, for a change from Wagner, outside leg, Starc misses his flick and is hit on the pads.
Full and around middle, pushed down the ground.
Nathan Lyon walks out now. Could be the last man in.

OUT! Caught! Wade is out of here. And, he is very, very distraught. A short ball, outside off, Matthew looks ready to punish it and pulls it really, really hard. But to his horror, he picks out Jeet Raval to perfection at deep mid-wicket! Surely, he did not want to get out this way? He takes some time and then trudges off.
FOUR! Full and wide outside off, Wade reaches out and slashes hard. Gets a thick outside edge which flies over point to the fence. NO BALL signalled.
Around off, watchfully defended.
Outside off, left alone.
FOUR! WHOOSH! Wade is looking forward to take on de Grandhomme. Full and wide outside off, Matthew reaches out and blasts it wide of mid off to the boundary at cover!
Outside off, left alone.
Mitchell Starc comes in to face the short ball music.

OUT! Caught down the leg side! Wagner gets the first wicket of the afternoon. In a way, it is good for Australia that Cummins is gone. They would not want their premier bowler to get injured to this short stuff. A length ball, outside leg, Pat looks to tickle but only manages a thin inside. Watling catches and appeals but PC is going nowhere. Now, he looks at the umpire who raises his finger and Cummins is happy to go. Wagner two away from a 5-fer in this innings.
A short ball to the all-rounder. Around leg, rising sharply, but Cummins does well to fend it down, well in front of short leg.

Well bowled, well played! Wagner tests Wade's concentration with a full ball but the batsman is aware and ready. Flicks it towards fine leg for the first runs off Wagner this morning. The crowd cheers. So Wagner will now bowl to Cummins for the first time today.
A short ball, around middle and leg, Matthew looks to shoulder arms and is hit right on the bread basket!
Full and around middle, watchfully defended.
Expectantly, a short ball, down the leg side, Wade offers no short and is hit on the left arm.
A bouncer to end the over, outside off, Pat sways away. So we are back to the Wagner-Wade duel.
Outside off, pushed straight to cover.
Full and straight, around off, pushed down the track.
Point goes back now.

FOUR! WHAM! The first real bad ball of the day. A short one, wide outside off, Cummins is up in a flash on seeing that and punches it through the covers. It is in the gap and races to the fence. Cummins moves to 13 now.
FOUR! A bit too straight. Angling onto the pads, Cummins is alert and tickles it to the fine leg fence.
Full and around middle, worked straight to short mid-wicket.
A bouncer to finish, around leg, Wade ducks again.
Full toss now, MW misses out, flicking it straight to short mid-wicket.
Down the leg side, Matthew lets it go again. That was not far from the elbow.

FOUR LEG BYES but dead ball signalled. A bouncer, down the leg side, Wade does not offer any shot. The ball hits his right arm and goes to the fine leg fence. The batsmen start to run but umpire Nigel Llong signals a dead ball, as the batsmen did not offer any shot.
Another bouncer, ducked again. How long will this duel go on? How long will Wagner keep on bowling bouncers? Till eternity. How long will Wade keep on leaving them alone? Patience-tester.
A bouncer, down the leg side, ducked under.
One more leave outside off. De Grandhomme, as usual, testing the patience of the batsman.
Outside off, quietly left alone.
Full and around off, watchfully defended.
A length ball around off, Pat looks to defend but the ball bounces a shade extra, takes the outside edge and lands in front of wide first slip. Actually, it is almost a second slip.
Around middle worked wide of mid on for a couple. The lead is now 421. The stand moves to 11.
A length ball, around off, coming in, Cummins looks to flick but misses and is hit on the pads. There is a mild LBW shout but that looked too high.
Down the leg side again, left alone.

OUCH AGAIN! Wagner is softening Wade up. He is giving that nasty smile but Wade is smiling even nastier! Is he thinking, 'Wait till you face Starc or Cummins, mate'? A short ball, outside leg, Matthew does not know how to play that, so just offers no shot. The ball hits him on the arm guard but he shows no pain.

OUCH! That has hurt. Wade is wincing in pain. A short ball, around leg stump, Matthew looks to tuck it to the leg side but the ball bounces sharply and pings him on the gloves of the bottom hand. Did that hit a crack? MW immediately takes his gloves off, walks away a touch but then makes himself ready to face. Tough man.
Full and around middle and leg, tucked towards short leg.
Another bouncer, around middle and off, Matthew ducks again.
A bouncer, on middle, Wade ducks.
Neil Wagner to bowl from the other end. 17-2-40-2 so far.
First runs of the day. Full and down the leg side, Cummins tickles it towards fine leg for a couple.
Full and down the leg side, PC looks to flick but misses and is hit on the pads. The ball rolls to the leg side.
Another bouncer, around middle, Pat ducks.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Full and around middle, pushed towards mid on.
A bouncer to start the day, Cummins ducks.

The umpires and the Kiwis are out in the middle but the batsmen aren't. Because Pat Cummins is at the boundary ropes but where is Matthew Wade? Somewhere in the dressing room. Now, he walks down the stairs. Now, the crowd cheers. Colin de Grandhomme to start off proceedings on Sunday, to Pat Cummins. Here we go...

Runs are not an issue. 350 would have been enough as a target on this deck and the Aussies have crossed 400. Given that the wickets generally tend to fall in the final session, the tactics from the hosts would be to try and bat as long as possible. The cracks on the pitch have started to widen, so batting certainly won't be easy. Can New Zealand bowl the Aussies out quickly and get a good part of the day to themselves to bat?

11 wickets fell on Day 3. But crucially, 5 of those came in 1 session. To add to that, those 5 came in the span of 67 balls. That is a shade over 11 overs. Really, as Brendon Julian remarked last evening on air, it is difficult to spot the pink ball under floodlights, but more so once it is past 7.30 pm local. New Zealand found it very difficult on Friday, Australia found it even more on Saturday. That last session yesterday has just quickened this game, which might enable us to have an off on Monday. Hello and a warm, sorry, HOT welcome to the fourth day's play of the first Test between Australia and New Zealand in Perth.
... DAY 4, FINAL DAY? ...

That's all from a lively Day 3. It was a tough day for the visitors but they will be happy with how they bowled in the latter stages of the day. It still looks difficult for the Kiwis to make a comeback with the lead already above 400 for Australia. Can they perform a complete turnaround or will the Aussies continue destroying opponents at home? Join us on Sunday at 1300 Local (0500 GMT) for the penultimate day of this Test match. Till then, cheers take care!

Australia had a good outing with the bat until the last session. Joe Burns and Marnus Labuschagne both scored half tons propelling the Aussies to a lead of 381. However, after that things went haywire for the hosts as their downward spiral started in the last session of the day. They collapsed from 131/1 to 160/6, all within the last hour giving the Kiwis a glimmer of hope when it seemed like they were down and out. However, the Aussies stay still on top with a lead of 417 runs and 4 wickets in hand. If the hosts manage to set a target of around 500, they will be more than happy.

The day started in a very good way for Australia as they dismissed New Zealand for a meagre 166 runs. Starc was the star for them as he took a 5-fer and pretty much dismantled the Kiwi batting order. The only players who could come out with some credit for the visitors were Ross Taylor and Kane Williamson who scored 80 and 34 runs respectively. Except for Colin de Grandhomme and these two, no one could even get to the double-digit mark, a rare sight for the Kiwis.

Tim Southee says that when the lights came on,  something happened off the pitch and it becomes a lot more interesting. On being asked about how the absence of one of their bowlers (Lockie Ferguson) has affected them, Southee says that they are a team of scrappers and they all fight for each other. Adds that it is hot out there but they know that they have to do the job ahead of them.

30 overs, 92 runs, 5 wickets. That certainly gives you the entire picture of the last session. The Kiwis have made a superb comeback very late on Day 3 and are now walking off the pitch after a tiring day of cricket. The Australians will be disappointed after having bossed the proceedings so far in the Test match. With the players going off, Southee has stopped for an interview. Let's see what he has to say!
Full delivery on middle, Wade defends it back to the bowler. STUMPS ON DAY 3.

Just short! Wade is lucky here! Good length ball on middle and leg, Matthew looks to flick it but it goes off the inside edge onto the pads and lobs towards Latham at short leg. Tom dives to catch it but it falls short.
Back of a length ball on middle, Cummins flicks it to mid-wicket and takes a single.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Cummins looks to drive it but fails to get any bat on it.
Bowls a bouncer on leg, Wade looks to duck but gets hit on the shoulder. It goes towards the leg side. The batsmen take a run. The umpire gives it as a leg bye.
FOUR! Full toss on leg, Wade flicks it through square leg for a boundary.
On a good length on off, Cummins blocks it off the front foot.
On a length on middle, Cummins flicks it to mid-wicket.
WIDE! Bowls a bouncer, Cummins easily ducks under it.
Bowls a yorker on middle, Cummins does well to dig it out.
Good length delivery on middle, Cummins defends it off the back foot.
On a good length on middle, Cummins defends it off the front foot.
Short delivery on leg, Cummins flicks it just past short leg.
Bowls a bumper again, Wade ducks under it.
Bowls a bouncer outside off, Wade sways away from it.
Bowls a bouncer, Wade lets it sail through to the keeper.
On a good length on middle, Wade blocks it off the front foot.
Full delivery on off, Wade drives it to covers again.
Full toss on off, Wade plays it to covers.
Back of a length ball on the pads, Cummins tucks it to mid-wicket.
Fullish ball down the leg side again, Pat looks to flick it but fails to put any bat on it.
Short ball around middle, Cummins is ready for it and ducks under it.
Good length ball down the leg side, Cummins looks to flick but misses it.
Pat Cummins is the new batsman in.

OUT! TIMBER! Australia are collapsing under the lights at Perth. Are New Zealand in with a chance? Good length ball tailing back in, Paine looks to flick it but the ball sneaks between the bat and pad, going onto hit the middle stump. The Australian skipper looks surprised and is having a look at the pitch before making his way back to the pavilion. The Kiwis bowling with a spring in their steps now. Can they take another wicket before Stumps?
BOUNCER! It is bowled around leg stump, Paine ducks under it.
Another bouncer, Wade is not able to get his bat at it and is hit on the body.
Bouncer again, Wade evades it.
Wagner follows up the misdirected knuckle ball beautifully by bowling a perfect yorker on the off pole. Wade does well to dig it out.
Knuckle ball by Wagner, it is a full toss on the pads. Wade flicks this one towards mid-wicket.

Bouncer on middle and off, Wade looks to defend by getting on top of it but the ball hits the gloves. Wagner stares at Wade in his followthrough and Wade gives a look back. Finally signs of some fire in the contest.
Length ball down the leg side, worked towards the leg side.
Tim Paine, the skipper, walks out to bat next.

OUT! TAKEN! Southee gets another wicket and this time it is Travis Head. Wickets falling like nine-pins for Australia right now. Southee bowls a short ball down the leg side, it stays a touch low after pitching. Head looks to help it fine down the leg side but he does so uppishly. Colin de Grandhomme at leg gully takes a simple catch and half the Australian side back in the hut now.
WIDE! Bowls a bouncer outside leg, Head sways away from it. The umpire gives it wide for height.
Bowls a bouncer, Head lets it sail through to the keeper.
On a length on middle, Head nudges it towards the leg side.
FOUR! Nicely played! Short delivery on leg angled into the ribs, Travis flicks it towards fine leg for a boundary.
Good length delivery on off, Head defends it off the back foot.
Short delivery on leg, Head nudges it towards the leg side.
Bouncer on middle and off, ducked under.
This time a back of a length ball on middle and leg. Wade looks to defend but gets hit on the thigh pad. The ball goes to the right of Watling who makes a diving stop.

Appeal but nothing doing! Another bouncer, on middle and off. Wade looks to fend at it but fails to do so and the ball flies towards keeper BJ Watling. He takes the catch and appeals but the umpire is unmoved. No reviews left for New Zealand. Replays roll in and show that it hit the arm guard.
On the pads again, Head flicks it towards the square leg region and takes a single to get off the mark.
Down the leg side, Head looks to flick it fine down the leg side but misses.
Still no signs of declaration as Travis Head walks in to bat. With 30 mins to go for the end of day's play doesn't seem like Paine will declare.

OUT! CAUGHT! Steven Smith now departs and Australia lose 2 wickets in quick succession! Wagner bowls a bouncer this time, on middle and leg. Smith looks to pull this powerfully but does not get the perfect timing on it. The ball goes a bit uppishly to the right of Jeet Raval at square leg who tumbles to that side and takes the catch. Smith looks really disappointed as he goes back to the pavilion. Australia have to be careful here not to lose wickets in a heap.
Outside off, Wade shoulders arms to this one.
Bowls a bouncer outside leg, Wade ducks under it.

FOUR! Southee tries the short ball tactic with Wade at the other end. Wade is up for the challenge as he pulls it through square leg. There is no one manning that area as the ball crosses the ropes in a flash.
Good length delivery on middle, Wade keeps it out.
On a good length on off, Wade defends it off the back foot.
Short delivery on leg, Smith pulls it through mid-wicket for a single. Australia are effectively 400/3.
On a good length on off, Wade defends it off the back foot.
Bowls a bouncer, Wade easily ducks under it.
Short delivery on middle, Smith pulls it through mid-wicket for a run.
Short again on leg, Smith pulls it to short fine leg.
Short of a length delivery on middle, Smith looks to defend but gets hit on the glove.
Length delivery on off, Smith taps it to point.
Length ball outside off, Wade opts to leave this one.
Bouncer again to Wade, he ducks under it this time.
Wade goes back in his crease and defends this length ball off the back foot.
Bouncer straight up to Wade! He does well to evade it.
Matthew Wade is the next batsman in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Burns is a goner and Australia lose their third wicket. Southee bowls a well-directed bouncer, on middle and off. Burns looks to hop and get over the ball in an attempt to keep it down. He only manages to get his glove on it. The ball flies towards the gully region where Henry Nicholls takes an easy catch. Southee gets his 2nd wicket of the innings and Australia are now 398/3 effectively.
Length delivery down the leg side, Burns looks to flick but misses it.
Short again, this time Smith goes for the pull but misses out to time it well.
Back of a length ball, Smith blocks it towards the leg side.
Outside off, left alone.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Another shortish length ball outside off, Burns cuts it through point for a single.
Back of a length ball around off, Burns pulls it towards mid-wicket.
Length delivery on middle, Steven nudges it towards square leg.
FOUR! That is put away! Short delivery on leg, Smith pulls it through square leg. The fielder tries to stop it but it goes through him into the fence.
Now this one shoots off! Good length delivery on off, Smith looks to defend but the ball rises on him. He somehow manages to keep it down off his gloves.

Huge appeal for LBW but not out says the umpire. No reviews left for the Kiwis. Anyway, that looked to be pitching outside leg. It pitched around leg and kept low. Smith looks to flick but mises to get hit on the pads. Southee and the Kiwis appeal but nothing doing.
WIDE! Bowls a bumper again, Smith ducks under it. The umpire gives it wide for height.
Bowls a bouncer outside leg, Smith sways away from it.
On middle, turned towards square leg.
Shortish and outside off, cut towards gully where the fielder does well to move to his right and field.
Full and on off, Smith flicks it towards mid-wicket where Santner misfields and allows a single.
Another short of a length ball but down the leg side. Smith lets it go to the keeper.
Bouncer on middle, Smith ducks under it.
Short of a length ball on middle, pulled behind square for a single.
Good length ball around off, Burns pushes it back to the bowler who gets to his right and fields.
FOUR! Wow! From the middle of the bat. Full and on off, Smith drills it past the bowler and into the fence. Brilliantly timed this one.

FOUR! Driven handsomely! Full and outside off, Smith gets to the pitch and slams it to the left of the short cover fielder. The ball races to the fence in a jiffy. Nowhere near the line of the delivery but superb hand-eye coordination fetches him these runs.
Good length ball around off, tapped towards point.
Another ball outside off, Smith makes another leave.
Outside off, Smith lets it be.
Full and on middle, Smith pushes it towards mid on off the front foot.
Tim Southee is back on. 12-4-39-1 are his figures so far.
Bumper but outside off, Burns lets it be.
On middle, Smith turns it behind square leg for a single to get off the mark.
Down the leg side. Smith comes across the off pole and allows the ball go through to the keeper.
Good length ball around off, Smith defends it out coming forward.
Steven Smith walks into bat. Still no signs of declaration from the Aussies. How long are the Aussies planning to bat? Still a long toil for the Kiwis in the field.

OUT! Caught! Wagner strikes. Gets him second time in a row. He has persisted with the short stuff and finally it pays the dividend for him. Another bouncer on middle, Labuschagne takes the challenge and goes for the pull but he cannot time it to his liking. It lobs towards Santner at mid-wicket who takes it easily. A  fine innings from him comes to end.
Bouncer and around off, Marnus blocks it back to the bowler.

Drinks! The lead continues to grow. No signs of declaration from the Aussies as yet. Kiwi bowlers continue to toil hard but without any success. Both Burns and Labuschagne have got to their respective fifties and would look to put the foot on the gear now. Let's see if Paine declares tonight and asks the Kiwis to face a few overs before Stumps. The broadcasters have got the two batters for a chat. Marnus says that the pitch is showing the variations. Burns says that the wicket is tough and jokes that youngsters like Marnus need glucose to keep going.
FIFTY FOR LABUSCHAGNE. His 6th in Tests. What a fabulous year he is having. A full ball outside off, Labuschagne drives it through covers and takes a single.
Shortish and on middle, pushed towards mid on.

NOT OUT! Labuschagne is well in! Floated delivery on middle, Marnus flicks it towards mid-wicket. Marnus wants the run but Burns sends him back. The fielder fires a direct hit at the keeper's end. It is referred upstairs. The replays show that Labuschagne was well inside the crease.
Run out appeal taken upstairs. Looks safe. It is safe.
Full delivery on middle, Burns drives it through mid on. The batsmen take a single.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Burns defends it out.
Flighted delivery on middle, Burns drives it to long on for a single.
Just behind good length and outside off, pushed towards gully with an angled bat.
Full and around off and middle this time, Burns pushes it towards the leg side.
Full and on the pads, flicked towards mid-wicket.
WIDE! Another one for height. Wagner bends his back and bowls short. This one shoots way over the head of Burns. The umpire stretches arms once again.
Another ball which does not bounce! It pitches on shortish length but does not rise. Burns does well to defend it out.
Short on middle, pulled towards mid-wicket.
Short again, pushed towards mid on for a single.
WIDE! Another extra, third wide from Wagner. He goes short again but way over the head of the batter. Called wide.
Fuller and around off, turned towards right of mid-wicket for a single. 3 away from another half ton.
Flatter one around off this one, pushed towards mid on.
Full and on middle, this time Labuschagne sweeps it past the diving short fine leg fielder for a couple of runs.
Another ball on the pads, Labuschagne flicks it but straight to fine leg.
On the pads, worked towards short fine leg.
Santner flights it and bowls it around off, ML pushes it back to Santner.
Mitchell Santner to bowl now.
Wagner looks to bowl another short ball but this one does not rise enough. Burns does well to keep it out.
Fuller and just around off, tapped towards point.
Another back of a length ball outside off, Burns lets it be again.
Another bouncer! Burns ducks under it.
Short and outside off, Burns looks to pull but gets a bottom edge which goes to the left of the keeper who dives to stop it well.
Back of a length ball on middle, Marnus pulls it towards fine leg for a single.
Neil Wagner comes back on! 7-0-25-0 are his figures so far.
In the channel outside off, left alone.
Around off this one, tucked towards the leg side and a quick run taken.
Outside off, left alone.
6th Test half ton for Joe Burns. A very well composed one from him. A full ball around off, Burns pushes it through covers and takes a single to reach the landmark.
Short ball on middle, Marnus pulls it towards deep square leg for a single now.
Brilliant running between the wickets! On a length on middle, Labuschagne flicks it through mid-wicket. He calls for two and Burns responds quickly.
Full delivery on off, pushed to point.
Short ball on middle, Labuschagne pulls it to fine leg and takes a single.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Good length ball on off, Burns looks to defend it but it goes off the inside edge past the stumps.  A single taken.
Outside off, Burns pushes it to point.
BEATEN! Beautiful bowling! Full delivery outside off with extra bounce, Burns pushes at it from inside the crease but misses it completely. Watling collects it near his head.
Outside off, Marnus offers no shot to this one.
Length delivery outside off, Burns guides it towards point for a run.
Short of a length delivery, Labuschagne pulls it over mid-wicket. The batsmen take a single.

Aleem Dar is down injured it seems. Kiwi physio is out to check after him. He collided with Santner while trying to stay away from the line of the throw from Southee. Some magic spray being applied. He now gets up, does some walking. Well, his knee is getting taped up. Takes a pain killer too. He is now ready to go.

Good length ball just outside off, Labuschagne tucks it towards the leg side. Burns wants a single. Labuschagne is not interested. Southee gets to the ball and aim the stumps at the non-striker's end. Burns dives to make his crease. However, Southee misses his shy at the stumps. There is a collision between umpire Aleem Dar and Santner. Mitchell was probably coming to collect the throw while Dar was trying to stay away from the firing line. Aleem Dar is down.
Nicely bowled! Bouncer on middle, Labuschagne does well to sway away from it.
Good length ball just outside off, Burns guides it towards third man and gets three closer to his half ton.
Again outside off, Labuschagne lets it go.
Outside off, Marnus shoulders arms to this one.
Length delivery on middle, Labuschagne flicks it through square leg. The batsmen get two runs.
On a length on middle, Marnus flicks it to mid-wicket.
Good length delivery on middle, Labuschagne defends it out.
On a length on middle, Labuschagne flicks it to mid-wicket.
Full delivery outside off, Burns drives it through covers. Two runs taken.
Short and outside off, Burns cuts it through point. The batsmen get two runs.
Length delivery on middle, Labuschagne flicks it through mid-wicket for a run.

FOUR! Why is there no third man in place? If there was a fielder placed it would have gone straight into his hands. Short and outside off, Labuschagne plays an upper cut over third man for a boundary.
Good length delivery on off, Labuschagne defends it out.
On a good length on off, Labuschagne defends it off the front foot.
Tim Southee back on. Searching for his second.
Good length delivery on middle, Burns keeps it out.
Outside off, Burns offers no shot to this one.
On a good length on middle, Joe defends it off the front foot.
Good length delivery on off, Burns defends it out.
Length delivery on off, Burns plays it to point.
On a length on middle, Burns flicks it to mid-wicket.
Flatter around off, Labuschagne keeps it out.
Shortish and on off, Burns goes back and then comes forward to turn it behind square for a single. 100 comes up for the Aussies. The lead touches 350 too.
FOUR! Second one off the over. Santner bowls it short and wide. This time Burns waits on the back foot and cuts it through point for a boundary.
Full and around off, Burns comes forward and keeps it out.
On middle, turned towards mid-wicket for a run.

FOUR! 50-run stand is up! Brilliant use of the feet from Marnus. Santner flights this outside off, Labuschagne skips down the track and slams it over the cover region and into the fence. Brilliant stand this one. Also, the boundary brings up 1000 Test runs for Labuschagne in 2019.
Fullish and outside off, Burns keeps it out.

Shortish length ball outside off, Labuschagne waits for the ball and then guides it through gully and second slip. The ball races to the fence but Taylor gives it a chase and makes a sliding stop to save a run.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
No Ball! De Grandhomme oversteps now. Fuller ball around off, Burns looks to flick but gets a leading edge which goes towards cover for a single.
Outside off, it is left alone.
On the pads this time, Marnus looks to work it fine down the leg side but gets hit high on the pads. The ball rolls towards square leg and the batters cross for a leg bye.
WIDE! This time Grandhomme bends his back and bowls a bouncer but it is way over the head of the batsman there. Wided by the umpire.
Full on off, driven firmly by Labuschagne but straight to the cover fielder again.
Tossed up delivery on middle, Burns keeps it out.
Loopy delivery on off, Marnus punches it towards point for a single.
Flighted delivery on middle, Marnus flicks it through mid-wicket. The batsmen pick up a couple.
Tossed up delivery on off, Labuschagne comes down the track and plays it back towards the bowler.
Floated delivery on off, Burns plays it towards covers for a run.
Full delivery on off, Burns drives it to covers.
Full and on off again, ML this time drives it to mid on.
Fuller and around off, Labuschagne drives well but straight to the cover fielder.
Landed around off, Labuschagne keeps it out.
Good length ball just outside off, Marnus lets it be.
Fuller and outside off, Burns leans and pushes it towards cover for a single.
Good length ball on middle, worked towards mid-wicket.
Colin de Grandhomme to bowl from the other end. 8-1-15-0 are his figures so far.
Nicely bowled! Fires this one on the stumps line, Labuschagne gets his bat down in time to keep it out.
Around off, it is defended.
Another ball on middle, Burns this time works it towards square leg and crosses for a run.
Slightly quicker and on middle, Labuschagne turns it with the spin towards square leg for a run.
Gives this one a lot of air and lands it around off again. Labuschagne blocks it out nicely.
Santner starts with a fullish ball around off, Burns comes forward to defend but the ball takes the inner half of the bat and goes towards square leg for a single.

We are back for the third session. The New Zealand players are out in the middle. Joe Burns and Marnus Labuschagne will resume their innings for the hosts. Mitchell Santner will start the proceedings for the final session of Day 3.
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

74 runs from the session for Australia and their lead now reads 325 runs. While they have lost the wicket of Warner, Burns along with Labuschagne have added 31 runs in 9 overs. The Kiwis have bowled good lines and lengths but have not been able to get wickets. A dropped catch from de Grandhomme and the run out opportunity missed by Santner, these are two things the Kiwis might talk about in this break. The two reviews that they've lost might trouble them going ahead. Now, how many more Australia would feel safe with? Will they force the Kiwis to bat tonight? Will be interesting to see what approach the Australians come out with. Do join us back for the final session.
Around off, solidly defended. TEA ON DAY 2, AUS LEAD BY 325!
Dropped short! Short delivery on middle, Burns pulls it uppishly but it goes on the bounce to the square leg fielder.
Full on middle, flicked through mid-wicket for a single.
BEATEN! Good length ball outside off, Labuschagne looks to drive it but fails to get any bat on it.

NOT OUT! Waste of a review! Watling was confident in his appeal. Good length ball tailing in, Labuschagne fails to read it and decides to leave it. It hits the pocket of the trouser and goes to the keeper. Watling appeals after collecting it but the umpire says no. After some thought, the Kiwis go for the review. They have lost one already. There was a distance between bat and pad so there was no chance of there being bat on it. The Ball Tracker then rolls in and it confirms that Marnus was hit on the pocket outside off. The impact won't matter as Marnus left the ball alone but the ball was going on to miss the stumps by a mile. Poor review from Kiwis and they have lost their second review as well.

LBW appeal taken upstairs by the Kiwis. Labuschagne is the man in question. The impact does not matter here as Labuschagne did not offer any shot. Well, it looks like the Kiwis will lose their last review as well. The Ball Tracker rolls in and confirms that it is away from the stumps and it is well over too.
Full delivery on off, Marnus drives it to mid off for nothing.
On middle, flicked to deep square leg and picks up a single.
Flatter delivery outside off, ML punches it to deep cover and picks up a couple.
Full delivery on middle, Marnus flicks it to mid-wicket.
Delicate touch! Flatter delivery outside off, Labuschagne waits for it and then guides it through gully for a couple. Wagner, the man with a lot of stamina, hares after it and cleans it up.
Floated delivery on the pads, Burns sweeps it to deep square leg for a single.
Flatter delivery on the pads, Burns attempts to work it on the leg side but gets hit on the pads.
Shortish ball around off, Labuschagne taps it back to the bowler.
Around off, Labuschagne keeps it out off the front foot.

Edged but does not carry to Taylor at first slip. Full ball around off, this time Labuschagne is drawn into the shot as he drives. The ball takes the outside edge and goes towards Taylor at first slip but it goes on the bounce. He does well to field it.
Another short ball outside off, Labuschagne cuts it through gully and picks a couple.
Shortish length ball, closer to off pole again. Labuschagne has his stumps covered as he allows the ball go to the keeper.
Fullish length ball just outside off. Labuschagne lets it be.
Colin de Grandhomme is back on. 6-1-11-0 are his figures so far.
On a length on off, pushed towards point.

Well fielded! Floated ball on off, Joe dances down the track but does not get to the pitch of it at all this time. He still plays the drive straight down the ground but Santner is quick to bend on his knees and collect it. Mitchell then looks to throw it back at Burns but does not do so. Burns has a wry smile on his face.
Flatter delivery on the pads, Joe looks to work it down the leg side but gets hit on the pads.
FOUR! Beautiful shot and some lovely footwork! Santner bowls a flighted ball on middle, Burns takes a few quick steps ahead and hammers it straight down the ground. One bounce and into the fence.
Floated ball down the leg side, Joe looks to flick it but misses it.
Flatter delivery on middle, Burns blocks it out onto the pitch.
Another short one on middle, Marnus defends it back to Wagner.
Short ball outside off, Labuschagne lets the ball go to the keeper.
On a length on off, ML rocks on his back foot and blocks it to cover.
Short ball on middle, Marnus pulls it to mid-wicket.
Back of a length delivery on middle, Labuschagne defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Shot! Labuschagne is continuing his form in this innings as well! Back of a length delivery outside off, Marnus rocks on his back foot and cuts it through point for a boundary.
The batsman rocks onto the back foot and punches the ball.
Flatter delivery on middle, Burns defends it off the back foot.
OHH! That was close! Quicker delivery on middle which almost brushes the pad of Burns. He, luckily gets his bat down in time and guides it to point.
Flighted ball on middle, Marnus comes down the track and flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Some spin immediately. Flatter delivery outside off going away from the batsman, Labuschagne looks to defend it but it goes past the outside edge of the bat.
Starts with a tossed up ball outside off, Burns drives it to deep cover and picks up a single.
Mitchell Santner is into the attack for the first time.
Make that two leaves in a row. In the channel outside off, Marnus lets it be.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Another short of a length ball, Labuschagne pushes it towards point.
Short for Burns too. He pulls it towards deep square leg and takes a single.
Defended off the front foot by the batsman presenting the full face of the bat.

Dropped! De Grandhomme puts down Labuschagne! He made all the ground by running to his right but cannot hold on. A well directed bouncer on middle, Labuschagne goes for the pull but there is extra bounce on that one and the ball comes slowly as well. As a result, he top edges it towards mid-wicket. Colin runs back from short mid-wicket, gets to the ball, puts in a dive but spills it in the end. How costly will it be? A single taken.
Full and outside off again, another nice looking drive straight to mid off again.
Overpitched and outside off, Burns drives it nicely but straight to the mid off fielder.
Full and outside off, Burns drives it towards cover where de Grandhomme fumbles but it does not cost them a run.
Brilliant running between the wickets! A good length ball on the pads, Labuschagne flicks it towards deep mid-wicket and runs three before the fielder can return the ball to the keeper.
AUSTRALIA'S LEAD NOW READS 300! A shortish length ball on middle, Burns rolls his wrists and pulls it towards deep mid-wicket for a single.
Labuschagne is underway straightaway! A nice drive too. A fuller ball just outside off, Marnus drives it towards mid off and takes off for a quick single.

Another one which did not get up at all. Another bouncer attempt from Wagner. This is just outside off. Burns is not sure if he should leave it or play at it. He eventually lets it be. Watling collects the ball on the bounce.
Another shortish length, pushed towards gully with an angled bat.
Shortish on off again, Burns this time rides the bounce and defends it towards cover.
Variable bounce starting to come in play. Wagner tries bowling another bouncer outside off. It does not take off though and dies down as it goes to the keeper.
Shortish ball around middle, Joe hops in the crease and keeps it out.
FOUR! Brilliantly timed! Overpitched and outside off. Burns leans into the shot and drives it through cover-point. It races to the fence.
Marnus Labuschagne comes in to bat. The Aussies would hope the first innings centurion replicates his heroics once again and take the game away from the Kiwi grasp.

OUT! CAUGHT! Warner does not survive long after the LBW shout! After getting a start here as well, Warner gets out. Short of a length delivery on middle which hurried onto him, Warner looks to pull it but ends up top edging it. He then checks whether he won't get hit-wicket as he lost control of his willow. David then, as he goes to pick up his bat sees Blundell taking the catch at mid on and then walks off. Blundell, the substitute fielder, comes a few steps ahead and pouches it safely.

That goes off the cracks! But to the bowler. Full delivery on middle, Warner drives it straight back to the bowler. Southee attempts to collect it but it hits the crack and bounces extremely low, beneath his hands! Tim looks at Warner and then smiles.
The batsman has defended it by getting right behind the line of the delivery.

OHH! Impact was outside off! The impact might have just saved Warner there. Good length ball around off, Warner looks to defend it but misses it to get hit on the back pad. Southee puts in a huge appeal but the umpire shakes his head. Southee is seen talking to his skipper but it seems that Kane Williamson is not hearing it properly. In the end, they decide not to go for the review. The replays roll in and Ball Tracker shows that the impact was outside off. Good decision to not go for the review.
Outside off, left alone by Warner.
Full delivery on off, Warner shouts wait on as he defends this out to the off side.
Shortish ball around off, Warner taps it towards point for a single.

Another no ball! Second off the over. To trouble Warner with the short stuff, Wagner is putting a little too much effort and hence probably he is crossing the line there. Another bumper on middle and leg. Warner this time goes for the pull but does not connect. Wagner while returning to his mark, has a word with the umpire there, probably asking where he is landing.
Another back of a length ball but down the leg side. Warner ducks under it.
No Ball! Wagner oversteps again. He goes short and on middle again, Burns pulls it towards deep square leg for a single.
Full and just outside off, Burns pushes it towards cover. That came from the toe end of the bat.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
WIDE! Fullish and wide outside off, actually way outside off. Burns lets it be but Llong stretches his arms to signal it a wide.
Shortish length ball on middle, Warner tucks it behind square leg and gets a run.
Bowls a back of a length ball, but it is sprayed way down the leg side. Warner lets it be.
FOUR! Another boundary for Burns in this over! Joe after a slow start is starting to look good now. Good length ball outside off, Burns drives this through the gully region for a boundary.
OHH! Very full delivery on the pads, Burns looks to flick it but misses to get hit on the pads. There is a stifled appeal for LBW but nothing from the umpire.
Good length ball on off, Burns looks to defend it but it goes off the inside edge to the leg side.

FOUR! Beautiful shot! Southee bowls a full delivery outside off, Burns lunges forward and drives it through the point region for a boundary. The fielder chases after it from point but fails to get there.
Back of a length ball on middle, Joe defends it back to the bowler.
Full delivery outside off, Burns lets it go to the keeper.

DRINKS! Warner and Burns have played out the initial hour of this session. Interestingly, the Kiwis have kept things tight and have not allowed easy runs for  the Aussie openers. The Kiwis lost one of their reviews, in an attempt to see the back of the 'Bull' but turns out Warner did not glove it behind. Now that both Warner and Burns look settled, they would probably look for scoring opportunities while the Kiwis will hope to get a couple of quick wickets. Interesting hour coming up.
Another short one outside off, Warner looks to play the upper cut but misses it.
NO BALL! It is bowled way over, Warner is not worried and he lets the ball go to the keeper. The umpire signals it a no ball as the bowler has overstepped.

Ha ha ha! Intriguing reactions. A sharp bouncer from Wagner, Warner ducks and then gets ready to walk off towards square leg to switch off. But then, he has a look at Wagner and feels that he is going to be given a stare or a piece of advice.
BOUNCER! It is bowled around off, Warner lets it go to the keeper.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.

RUN OUT CHANCE MISSED! Poor judgement in running from the batsmen but Warner survives. He was nowhere in the picture. Burns defends this good length ball towards point and calls Warner for a single. Santner comes across, slides and collects it. He then has a shy at the keeper's end but misses it. Had he hit, Warner was a goner. Can Warner make NZ pay for it?
On a length on off, Burns defends it to cover.
Wagner bowls a full delivery on middle, Burns works it towards square leg and picks up a couple before Raval can chase it down from square leg.
Full delivery on middle and leg, Warner pushes it to mid on. Third maiden over for Southee.
Fullish ball on off, Warner is solid in defense and does so towards cover.
Outside off, Warner makes another leave.
Good length ball outside off, David lets the ball through to the keeper.
Good length delivery on off, blocked to cover.
OHH! Good length ball outside off, Warner looks to cut it but it goes off the bottom edge towards the slip cordon. No harm done though.
Tim Southee is back on!
On middle, defended back to the bowler by Burns.
Fullish delivery on middle, Warner tucks it to deep square leg and takes a single.
Good length ball around off, David pushes it to cover.
On a length on middle and leg, Warner works it to mid-wicket.
Full delivery on middle, Warner pushes it to mid on.
Full delivery on middle, David defends it off the front foot to mid off.
On a length outside off, Burns leaves it alone to the keeper.
Back of a length ball on off, Warner pushes it towards the cover region and picks up a single.
BEATEN! Back of a length delivery outside off, Warner attempts the pull shot but misses to get any bat on it.
Fullish ball outside the off stump line, David lets the ball go to the keeper.
Good length ball on middle, Warner solidly blocks it out to mid on.
Full delivery on off, Warner punches this to mid off and shouts a loud no to Burns.
This time goes full on middle does Wagner, Burns is solid in defense.
Fuller one outside the off stump line, Burns does not fiddle with it and lets the ball go to the keeper.
Fullish delivery outside off, Joe pushes it to covers for nothing.
Good length ball outside off, Burns lets the ball go to the keeper.
On a length on middle, Joe defends it out off the back foot.

FOUR! A loosener to start off from Wagner! A half volley outside off, Burns leans into his drive and drives it past the diving fielder at cover and into the fence. The fielder from mid off chases after it but fails to keep it inside the fence.
Neil Wagner is into the attack.

NOT OUT! Warner stays, New Zealand lose a review. Brilliant bowling from de Grandhomme. He dishes out a shortish length ball just around off and middle. Warner has to play at it. He hops and looks to defend but misses out. The ball hits something and goes towards second slip. The fielder there pouches it nicely. Kiwis are confident in their appeal. It seems like Warner is going off but maybe he was going towards square leg to switch off. Williamson though goes for the review. Let's find out. First up, it is Hot Spot. Nothing conclusive from it. Not the proper angle to view it. Here comes Snicko. No deflection as it goes past the gloves. Then as the ball passes the gloves, it hits the shoulder and there's the deflection of the same on the Snicko. Don't change your decision says Erasmus to Aleem Dar. Warner to continue, the Kiwis go one review down.

DRS TIME! It looked like Warner was going off but maybe he was going towards square leg to loosen his gloves. Was that off the gloves? Let's see in the replays. Looks like hitting the shoulder. Nothing conclusive on the Hot Spot. Snicko time. Nothing on the Snicko either. A deflection is there but it is of the ball hitting the shoulder and not bat. So Warner survives. New Zealand lose their review.
FOUR! Tickled nicely! Not a good ball this one. It is on the pads of Warner. All he needs to do is get a tickle, he does it nicely and it goes to the fence.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Another shortish length ball outside off, Warner this time is clear that he is going to let it go to the keeper.
Shortish and outside off, Warner first lets it be and when the ball goes past him, he tries to upper cut it but makes no connection.
On the pads, Burns guides it towards fine leg for a single.

Brute of a yorker from Southee. Warner looks to flick but misses out. A loud appeal from Southee and the players from slip cordon but umpire is not interested. Looked like a big inside edge on that one. No review taken from the Kiwis.
The batsman shows the full face of the bat and defends the ball off the back foot.
Beaten! This one kept low! A cross seamed ball just outside off, it pitches and then comes in as Warner looks to defend. Watling pouches it low in front of him. That cut him into half.
Good length ball outside off, Warner lets it be.
Around off on a good length, Warner defends it out.
Shortish length ball, closer to off. Warner covers his stumps and lets it be.
Full and on off, Burns drives it nicely but straight to mid off.
The batsman has played that off the front foot and into the ground.
Length ball around off, Burns pushes it towards point.

Finally, Burns is off the mark! Full and just outside off, Burns drives it through covers. Santner from point chases the ball down and keeps it to two. Brilliant effort from him. Burns though will be a relieved man now.
Landed on middle, Burns turns it towards square leg.
On off, Burns keeps it out.

Beauty to end the over! Length ball outside off, Warner thinks this will come in with the angle. However, Southee takes it the other way by rolling his fingers on the ball. Warner pokes and is beaten.
Good length ball just outside off, Warner defends it out.
FOUR! Full and outside off, Warner drives it through point nicely. The ball races to the fence. The boundary brings 7000 Test runs for Warner, 12th Australian to do so.

There is no obvious intent amongst the Aussie openers. Joe Burns needs some runs. It would be harsh to drop him for the second Test if he fails here, especially having scored more than 1000 runs with Warner in this format. The problem is, the competition is very high, with Usman Khawaja knocking the door. Joe might want to lock that door tight with Uzzie ready to burn it down.
In the channel outside off again but it is on a length. Warner shoulders arms.
Around off on a length, pushed towards cover.
Fuller and outside off, Warner thinks to go for the drive but then curbs his instinct at the last moment.
Outside off, it is left alone by Burns.
Good length ball around off, Burns pushes it towards mid off.
Around off, this time Warner pushes it towards point and takes a quick run.
Good length ball around off, Warner taps it towards the off side and shouts a loud no to his partner.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Beaten! Shortish length, not too wide off the off pole. Warner goes on the back foot to cut but makes no connection.
Shortish length ball, just outside off, Burns taps it towards gully. 20 balls and Burns is yet to get off the mark.
Good length ball angled into the right-hander. Burns punches it towards mid  on.
Around off, Burns comes forward and keeps it out off the front foot.
Fullish and driveable ball outside off. Burns is not falling for the trap as he lets it be. Two slips are waiting for the outside edge.
Outside off on a good length, it shapes away as it goes past Burns who allows it to go to the keeper.
On the pads, Warner looks to tickle it around the corner to get hit on the pads. The ball rolls towards fine leg and a leg bye is taken.

Nearly a drag on! Shortish length ball around off, Burns stays on the back foot and looks to block. He though manages an inside edge which drops near the stumps and then bounces over it. Burns survives a scare.
Fuller one, pushed towards cover.
Second leave in a row as de Grandhomme bowls it outside off on a good length.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Fuller one and on off, driven firmly but straight to the cover fielder.
Shortish length ball around off, Burns taps it off the back foot onto the pitch.
In the channel outside off, Warner lets it be.

Mike Hussey gets a bit nervous, when asked whether he would be happy with Australia declaring post Tea. Hussey says that he is not too sure, with so much time left in the game. His argument is that no total or target is safe with Taylor and Williamson in the opposition. And - Australia are a bowler short. So if wickets do not fall as per plan, then they could be in for some long toil in temperatures of 40-plus.
Good length ball around off, Warner keeps it out.

FOUR! Lovely timing! First boundary of the innings. Goes full just around off, Warner leans forward and drives it through mid off for a boundary. The mid off fielder gives it a chase but the ball wins the race.
Fuller and around off, it is defended off the front foot towards cover.
Fuller and just outside off, Warner drives it well but straight to mid off. Burns was probably interested for a single but Warner shouts a loud no.
Southee starts with a good length ball outside off, Warner has his stumps covered as he shoulders arms.
Tim Southee to bowl from the other end.
Another one in the corridor of uncertainty. Burns is not attacking these as he lets it go to the keeper. Colin needs to get closer to the timbers here.
In the channel outside off, Burns shoulders arms.
Good length ball around off, Burns keeps it out.
Outside off, it is left alone.
Around off, it is defended.
Shortish ball outside off, pushed towards short third man with an angled bat.
NO BALL! De Grandhomme oversteps on the first ball of his spell. Full ball on the pads, Warner tucks it towards square leg for a single.

We are back for the second session. David Warner and Joe Burns walk out to the middle. They survived one over before Lunch and now the duo will look to pile on the runs to take Australia to a further stronger position. Colin de Grandhomme will start the proceedings for the visitors in this session. Here we go...
... Day 3, Session 2 ...

So the one over has been ticked off by the Aussie openers. They will now look to bat deep post Lunch. Bat quickly or normally, we shall come to know after the break. A good session for the Aussies, piling on the pressure, in spite of losing Hazlewood. Their score now reads 251/0 and they might target 400. Or, a quickfire batting performance to get to 350 by Tea and then declare. Join us back at 3.40 pm local time (0740 GMT). 63 overs left in the day.
Full and on middle, Burns pushes it towards mid on to see off the over. THAT WILL BE LUNCH ON DAY 3.
Another one outside off on a good length, Burns lets it be. Last ball before Lunch coming up.
In the channel outside off first up for the right-hander. Unlike Warner, Burns is not lured as he shoulders arms.

That is very good umpiring. After the third ball, David Warner walked right up to where Joe Burns was batting and banged the pitch hard with his bat. Trying to tap the cracks and make them open a little. Nigel Llong sees that and straightaway walks up to the 'Bull' and prevents him from doing. Like a school kid who has been caught doing a mischief, Warner has his head down and does not even nod. But principal Llong still keeps yelling at him, all the time till Southee gets back to his mark!
Warner is underway! Another good length ball, this is on the pads, Warner tucks it towards fine leg for a single. 3 tricky balls for Burns then.
Good length ball around off, it is defended.
Beaten first up! Full and outside off, Warner is lured into the shot as he drives away from the body. Quite a risky shot this one at this moment of time. 5 more balls to survive before lunch.

That is it from the first Test then! Many expected Australia to win but sadly, there was barely any fight from the Kiwis. Probably the toss loaded things too heavily in the hosts' favour. Now, back to red-ball cricket. And the second game will be played on a memorable occasion. The Boxing Day. Join us on Thursday, 26th December, 2019 at 11 am local (0000 GMT) from the iconic Melbourne Cricket Ground. It is the same day when England kick off their much-awaited tour of South Africa. A big day awaits. ADIOS! TAKE CARE!

MITCHELL STARC HAS BEEN NAMED THE MAN OF THE MATCH. On being asked about the toughness regarding the heat and a bowler down, Starc says that it was very tough but praises all his mates, including Marnus Labuschagne, especially his bowling. On his refound form, Mitchell says that he has made some technical changes and with Andre Adams in the bowling setup, it has helped him immensely. Is looking forward to the break and playing some golf before the second Test.

Victorious Australian skipper, Tim Paine, is very happy to take a 1-0 lead. Believes that the first innings batting set the game up. Adds that bowling last is always in your favour. Praises the bowling attack for taking 20 wickets in 105 overs. Credits Lyon and Starc for being outstanding and also has a word of praise for Marnus Labuschagne.

New Zealand captain, Kane Williamson, manages to put on a smile. Admits that the heat was challenging and so was the opposition. Praises them for batting superbly in the heat and admires the smartness in bowling under the lights in the first innings. Agrees that the first innings with the bat cost his side the game as it was very difficult to bounce back after that. Wants his unit to take some time off and regroup for the second Test. Admits that the pitch was a lot different from the one at home but also says that international cricket is all about adjustment.

Nice to see this. Kane Williamson and David Warner are having a chat. They play for the same team in the Indian T20 League, Hyderabad. Both are smiling, clearly appreciating each other's efforts. Now, Starc joins them. Really good camaraderie. Now, the presentation comes up...

Nathan Lyon has a chat with Kate Loughnan. The offie praises the team for the commendable performance and is proud of the big boys for stepping up and beating the number 2 Test team in the world. On being asked about the magnitude of the win, Lyon says that Australia have been very consistent and he is not too surprised. Feels lucky to have dismissed Kane Williamson and cheekily says that he had no idea that he was on a hat-trick in the second innings. On Starc's 9-fer, 'Gary' calls him very special working his back side off consistently.

It was not as if New Zealand did not have anything in this game. Southee and Wagner got 4 each in the first innings while they combined to take 8 again in the second, as Southee got a 5-fer. With the bat, Ross Taylor's 80 gave them some respectability in the first innings while Watling and de Grandhomme's efforts in the second dig ensured that there was some fight shown. But clearly, they required more. Kane Williamson not performing in both innings hurt them.

For a change, Steven Smith did not do much. Neither did David Warner. But an upcoming youngster in Marnus Labuschagne stepped up. He got his third successive ton and almost got the record of becoming the first Aussie and just the third overall to score a hat-trick of 150s in Tests. His century ensured that New Zealand were on the back foot as Australia got to 416. Then, as one expected, Starc was menacing with the ball under lights and his 5-fer just pushed the Kiwis to the hilt. Once the 250-run lead was taken, there was no doubt who was going to win the game.

Was the game won even before it started? You never know. Trent Boult was ruled out and that gave immense strength and advantage to Australia. Boult with the pink ball might have done what Starc did and the game might have been in the balance. To add to that, Lockie Ferguson was ruled out of bowling on Day 2 and that hurt them very, very badly.

Right. Another win for Australia in a Day/Night Test. A complete drubbing of New Zealand. Half the battle was won at the toss and once they got past 400 in the first innings, it was always going to be an uphill task for the Kiwis to stay with them in the game.

OUT! EDGED AND TAKEN! Starc does not get a 10-fer. We do not have a Day 5. Lyon finishes things off. Full and outside off, Southee comes forward to defend but the ball spins in slightly, takes the outside edge and goes straight to first slip. An easy chance for Steven Smith this time and he makes no mistake. AUSTRALIA WIN BY 296 RUNS!

Australia will have to wait for the victory celebration. Lockie Ferguson does come out to bat at number 11. Starc may not mind that. A second 5-fer in the game awaits...

OUT! Caught behind and Starc has 9 in the match! A length ball, around middle, Wagner looks to defend but the ball angles away, takes the outside edge and goes to Tim Paine. Starc starts to celebrate and is that the end of the game? Will Lockie Ferguson come out to bat?

The moment Matthew Wade has been waiting all day. Neil Wagner has come in to bat. After being hit by a few bouncers this afternoon, Wade will be looking to be right in Wagner's ears. But we are going to have  a delay. The sky camera has got stuck, at around 12 feet over the pitch, right in the centre. There seems to be a power issue. Finally, it is sorted.

OUT! That is a stunning catch! The short stuff gets Santner. He was never looking comfortable and departs for a 8-ball duck. But what concentration from Travis Head! It is never easy to field for a fast bowler but Head did not move an inch. Normally, players take their eyes off and look for cover. But not Head. A short ball, right at the body from around the wicket, Mitchell cannot do much other than hop and tamely fend at it. The ball goes straight off the face of the bat, straight to silly point who just takes it calmly. Or makes it look pretty simple.

On a good length on middle, Santner blocks it off the back foot.
Short delivery again down the leg side, Santner does not bother to play at that.
Short of a length delivery down the leg side, Santner leaves it alone.
Tim Southee walks in at number 9, replacing Watling.

OUT! There is a faint mark on Hot Spot and Watling is caught down the leg side! A very bizarre moment for Australia. A short ball down the leg side, Watling got across and looked to fend but seemed to have missed. Now, there was a noise. Paine heard it. Or he looked to be the only one who heard it. He straightaway ran to the bowler in celebration and then started to appeal. But umpire Nigel Llong, seemingly looking frustrated at the continuous appeals from Australia all day, shook his head. For a change, Paine did not ask anyone. ANYONE. Smith at first slip did not move an inch while Starc was just looking to go back to his mark. Then suddenly, he sees his skipper go for the review and is clearly surprised, asking him whether he was sure! From the replays, to the naked eye, it looks the ball has hit the abdomen. But Hot Spot shows the tiniest of marks on the glove and then the abdomen! Nothing on the Snickometer but that does not matter. The decision is overturned and Watling has to depart. Well played, once again.

Massive shout for a catch down the leg side! Not out says, Nigel Llong. Paine takes the review. Starc himself is not sure and seems surprised that his skipper chose to review. A TINY MARK on the glove on Hot Spot. Nothing on Snicko. But the first evidence is enough. Miracle! Paine gets two reviews right!

On a pitch where the Aussies lost 5/30 odd last evening and the Kiwis themselves collapsed on Day 2, they have been wicketless so far. It is that time of the day when the sun goes down and batting becomes tougher but the resilience has been excellent. Here comes Pat Cummins again. 16-5-28-0 so far.

So! A bizarre way to go into the break. Nicholls might well have been out but was the correct protocol followed there? What was the third umpire checking? Was it a player's review or an umpire's review regarding the legality of the catch? Australia just strengthening their surge towards a 1-0 lead. 5 wickets left and around 35 overs pending. The floodlights will be switched on and Starc will be ready to swing that strawberry. Will we witness a Day 5? Join us back at 6 pm local (1000 GMT).

Tim Paine is giving an interview. He is happy with the way the session ended. Feels sorry for Nicholls that the ball hit the back of his bat. Hopes to take more wickets when the floodlights come on. Admits that it is challenging for both the keeper and the batsmen to face Nathan Lyon on such tracks.

OUT! CAUGHT! Well, a bit of a bizarre procedure there. Let us describe the events one by one. Tossed up delivery outside off, Nicholls lunges to defend but the ball comes in with the angle, hits the pads and lobs to silly point. Now, Travis Head takes it, celebrates and then appeals. Aleem Dar immediately raises his finger. Seeing that, Travis Head runs around in circles in jubilation while Nicholls asks the umpire the manner of his dismissal. On being informed that he has been given out caught, Nicholls has a long chat with Watling and then signals the 'T'. Now comes the bizarre part. From one side of the replays, it seems that the ball has hit the pad, then hit the back of the bat and dipped to Travis Head who has taken a very good catch, inches above the ground. But the third umpire is only checking the legality of the catch. Does that mean he is satisfied there is an edge? No Hot Spot is checked, nor Snicko. Eventually, the third umpire relays the message to Aleem Dar who signals it OUT once again. So - was this an umpire's review or a player's review? Something to ponder as TEA IS TAKEN.

Caught at silly point! But has Nicholls nicked it? He has taken the review. Replays seem to show that the ball has hit the back of the bat. This is strange. No Hot Spot is shown, or Snicko but the batsman is ruled OUT.
